<TEXT>
the vice presidency converts respectable 
politicians into champagnesipping wimps and ought to be abolished 
a political scientist says 
william gormley said richard m nixon hubert h humphrey and 
walter mondale were examples of vigorous congressmen who became 
victims of a job that has little authority 
gormley an associate director of the university of wisconsins 
robert m la follette institute of public affairs also said the 
office is outmoded because the founding fathers conceived of the 
vice presidency as an advisory post yet presidents today have 
plenty of advisers he said 
worst of all gormley said is the effect the vice presidency 
has on the people who hold the office 
the vice presidency turns a vigorous robust individual into a 
wimp he said after a few years as vice president even a 
previously vigorous and creative political leader turns into a 
wishywashy mealymouthed sycophant 
vice presidents have always been wimps nixon humphrey and 
mondale were all wimpy vice presidents he said 
in order to do the job as vice president they must play the 
role of a meek and humble servant a presidential loyalist a 
defender of the presidents position he said 
the country could easily turn to the secretary of state or the 
speaker of the house of representatives for a successor if a 
president were to die in office he said 
the secretary of state also could perform many of the vice 
presidents functions he said 
the secretary of state can sip champagne at diplomatic parties 
and look somber and dignified at state funerals gormley said 
the vice president is eminently dispensable 
</TEXT>
