<TEXT>
police ended a nearly 12hour standoff 
with an armed lebanese man barricaded in the libyan embassy by 
rushing in and grabbing the gunman after he had fallen asleep 
officials said 
no shots were fired in the incident thursday and a handful of 
libyan embassy employees who had been trapped on the top floors 
were not injured police said 
police identified the man as elibrahim edelbi 22 and said he 
had escaped from a prison in goettingen on july 8 along with a 
turkish accomplice who has since been recaptured 
edelbi was serving a threeyear prison term for assault police 
said 
for nearly 12 hours police negotiated with edelbi who pulled 
out a pistol inside the embassys firstfloor reception room after 
he was denied a visa for libya embassy employees were able to flee 
the building quickly or run to the upper floors leaving edelbi by 
himself police said 
he had become very weak since his escape and looked exhausted 
during the negotiations said ulrich fischer head of the bonn 
police team that captured edelbi 
fischers team was able to watch edelbi by making use of a video 
camera that is a normal part of embassy security 
at about 915 pm police noticed edelbi had fallen asleep and 
they rushed him fischer said 
finally he just fell asleep from exhaustion said fischer 
he did not offer us any resistance 
police said they did not know where edelbi got the pistol 
edelbi was taken to a local hospital for examination officials 
said 
a team of police officers negotiated with the gunman for almost 
12 hours by telephone as well as through a metalbarred door at the 
entrance to the structure 
he demanded that he not be returned to prison he said he 
wanted to go to libya because the libyans always help the 
lebanese said fischer 
police spokesman hans georg classen said edelbi was born in 
beirut but he said bonn police did not know how long edelbi had 
lived in west germany whether he had any relatives in this country 
or know any other details about the man other than his prison 
record 
edelbi had been at the prison in goettingen for about 18 months 
classen said 
shortly after the standoff began heavily armed police officers 
wearing combat gear climbed through a secondstory window into the 
embassy known as the libyan peoples bureau 
those officers guarded access to the upper floors of the 
fivestory building in case edelbi tried to take hostages from 
among the employees on the higher floors fischer said 
omar k bukhries head of the embassy had given police 
permission to enter the building classen said bukhries was able 
to escape through a side door shortly after the standoff began 
police sealed off the area after embassy employees signaled an 
alarm shortly before 10 am 
