<TEXT>
americans have indicated they would like to 
see more federal regulation of the 17 billionayear cosmetic 
industry which currently lacks stringent controls an official of 
the food and drug administration says 
heinz j eiermann director of the fdas division of cosmetic 
technology said people are often surprised to learn that 
cosmetics which usually contain chemicals have so few federal 
guidelines 
eiermann made his comments in a telephone interview thursday 
after a house subcommittee heard testimony about the potential 
danger of some of the chemicals in cosmetics 
rep ron wyden dore chairman of the small business panel 
said some of the chemicals in cosmetics can cause cancer birth 
defects central nervous disorders skin and eye irritations and 
allergic reactions 
wyden promised to have additional hearings in the fall to weigh 
whether congress should take action to enforce additional testing 
and labeling of cosmetics about 8000 chemicals are used in 
cosmetics and perfume 
he said the fda does not have the authority to test cosmetics 
for safety before they are sold and cannot require manufacturers 
to provide test data on a products safety 
the only actions fda can take are to seize contaminated products 
and to ask manufacturers to change their advertising claims he 
said 
retail products sold to consumers must be labeled as to 
contents but that regulation does not apply to products sold to 
business establishments such as hair styling salons 
eiermann said it is congress responsibility to decide whether 
americans want cosmetics to be subject to the same standards 
applied to food and drugs 
but he said the fda did a food survey in the 1970s and included 
questions about cosmetics there is a preponderance of the 
population they think the products should be regulated he 
said 
results of the study were never published because they were part 
of the broader survey he said 
the cosmetic toiletry and fragrance association a group that 
represents the industry said cosmetic companies are committed to 
safety because of this commitment personal care products are 
among the safest of any consumer products and are used confidently 
by millions of persons on a daily basisit said in a statement 
the industry has a program of selfregulation that involves 
testing ingredients the statement said 
beth shulman vice president of the united food and commercial 
workers international union said congress should pass legislation 
requiring that all cosmetic products contain ingredient labels 
secondly she said more studies need to be done to determine 
the longterm effects on people who use the chemicals 
dr james cone chief of the occupational health clinic at san 
francisco general hospital urged congress to take steps to warn 
consumers and beauticians about any possible health hazards in 
cosmetics 
he suggested that products contain detailed labels that clearly 
spell out the nature of any chemicals in the cosmetics and explain 
possible health hazards 
moreover the government should collect better information about 
the chemicals and their effects and remove any that are deemed 
dangerous cone said 
</TEXT>
