<TEXT>
the us army corps of engineers says it 
turned down a request for emergency diversion of great lakes water 
to the droughtdepleted mississippi river because the action would 
do little to help shipping 
the decision was based on analysis of water flow and economic 
considerations said robert page the armys assistant secretary 
for civil works after testifying thursday before the senate 
merchant marine subcommittee it was not politically motivated 
page said 
illinois gov james thompson and other officials whose states 
have an economic stake in the mississippi asked last month for an 
increase in water flow from the lakes to the river from 3000 cubic 
feet per second to 10000 cubic feet per second 
they asked that the increased flow continue for 100 days 
the officials said increasing the flow would enable barge 
traffic to resume movement down the mississippi the rivers level 
has fallen because of the drought and some 3000 barges were 
reported stranded as a result 
barge shippers have estimated losses as a result of the stalled 
shipping at up to 60 million 
but page said increasing the outflow to 10000 cubic feet per 
second would not do much to help mississippi navigation and shoals 
would continue to impede the flow of goods 
we will still have flow on the mississippi through the 
summer he said we see in the foreseeable future based on our 
forecast we dont need increased diversion at all 
don vonnahme director of water resources for the illinois 
department of transportation said the agency had no problems with 
the decision 
if they feel the waters wouldnt do any good then we 
certainly wouldnt want to take them out of the lake he said 
great lakes state senators praised the decision 
the corps position gives us more ammunition in the continuing 
struggle to prevent any diversion said sen carl levin a 
michigan democrat i have maintained that we should explore 
alternatives to diversion such as lightening the loads on barges 
or utilizing truck or rail for transporting goods 
sen donald riegle a michigan democrat said this decision 
will let us protect our water conserve it and use it in the 
proper ways in the future 
the governors of four great lakes states opposed the diversion 
and only thompson supported it among the leaders of the eight 
states surrounding the lakes canadian officials also protested the 
proposed diversion 
supporters of diversion argued the increased flow out of the 
lakes would have a minuscule impact on the great lakes but would 
have great benefits downriver 
opponents argued that the lakes water was needed in the midwest 
and northeast increasing diversion would set an unacceptable 
precedent and the federal government could not increase diversion 
without the concurrence of all eight governors of great lakes 
states 
</TEXT>
