president reagan appears all but certain to 
sign a disaster bill containing payments of up to 100000 for 
droughtstricken farmers the senate agriculture committee chairman 
says 
the prospects are virtual certitude that there will be a 
drought bill sen patrick j leahy dvt said thursday after 
the committee approved a blueprint that could cost up to 7 billion 
or even more 
we assured the president that we would stay within the budget 
and we will leahy said 
reagan said after touring droughtstricken illinois cornfields 
with gov james r thompson that he was a little edgy about 
proposed amendments that flooded into the agriculture committees 
wednesday night but he said he stood ready to approve the basic 
legislation 
i will sign it the minute it is delivered to me reagan said 
in an interview on radio station woc in davenport iowa he said in 
a speech that lawmakers should not use the bill as an excuse to 
rewrite farm programs 
drought relief should be just that drought relief reagan 
said partisanship should be kept out of the issue of drought 
relief politics must stop at the parched fields edge 
the government meanwhile declared ohio and missouri disaster 
areas because of the drought making farmers in those states 
eligible for emergency lowinterest loans officials from both 
states said 
thomas dayley spokesman for the agriculture department said 
the disaster designation had been requested by the governors of the 
two states 
other states logged as of thursday for official designation 
were alabama arizona arkansas california florida idaho iowa 
minnesota montana new york south dakota tennessee and texas 
in washington leahy and sen richard g lugar rind said at 
a news conference that bestguess estimates placed the cost of aid 
to crop growers at around 55 billion and to livestock producers 
at 1 billion to 15 billion 
overall drought costs however could be considerably higher 
than that with farm analysts saying the cost of an avalanche of 
federal crop insurance claims alone could reach 1 billion 
the bill would provide farmers with disaster payments capped at 
100000 for 65 percent of predrought expected earnings on crop 
losses in excess of 35 percent of their historical yields 
and both committees are studying ways to enrich the formula a 
bit for the hardest hit farmers in the grain belt 
in putting on the finishing touches senators added special 
provisions that could aid key industries 
one such plan would allow corn refiners who produce ethanol fuel 
to buy corn from federal stocks at 110 percent of the governments 
cost of acquisition influenced by drought crop prices have 
skyrocketed since much of the corn was acquired under the bill 
ethanol producers could buy up to 2 million bushels each every 
month 
senators said the bills costs could be offset by government 
savings primarily a reduction in deficiency payments due to the 
drought 
these payments to growers of wheat corn cotton rice and a few 
other crops represent the difference between the value of a 
farmers harvest at the market and its value at a socalled target 
price set by congress 
the budget calls for 17 billion in spending by the 
governmentowned commodity credit corp for deficiency payments and 
pricesupport loans 
but the market price of corn is now more than the target price 
and that would automatically mean a dramatic slash in program costs 
the market prices held for the rest of the year even if not 
though the cost to the government is going to be much smaller than 
expected estimates of the savings range from 5 billion to 10 
billion 
many farmers however already have received up to 40 percent of 
their deficiency payments in advance and unless rescued by 
legislation will have to refund all or part at a time when they 
have much reduced income the bill would allow them to keep what 
they have received in advance 
emergency feed programs for livestock producers would be 
expanded and capped at 50000 for each individual and a planned 
50cent per hundredweight cut in dairy price supports set for next 
year would be called off 
</TEXT>
