<TEXT>
a federal judge has upheld cape cod national 
seashore guidelines allowing offroad vehicles on an eightmile 
stretch of beach defeating conservationists who claim the vehicles 
threaten the fragile ecosystem 
us district judge david s nelson ruled that offroad vehicle 
driving on cape cods northern beaches is an appropriate public 
use and does not adversely affect the seashores natural 
scenic and aesthetic values 
the conservation law foundation massachusetts audubon society 
and the sierra club which sued over dune buggy use in 1981 
appealed the decision to the 1st us circuit court of appeals 
the conservationists contend that vehicles threaten shore bird 
nesting and the tender vegetation that stems erosion of the dunes 
they also say vehicles destroy the natural beauty and interfere 
with other beachgoers 
but nelson said in a ruling signed late last month that dune 
nesting and beach aesthetics are unaffected by the vehicles and 
that conflicts between drivers and other beach users are minimal 
under amended rules issued in 1985 vehicles are limited to the 
eightmile stretch from hatches harbor to high head in truro 
winter driving is prohibited and the beach is closed when tides 
beach configurations or bird nesting make the route impassable 
just one of the seashores six public beaches race point is 
open to drivers who must get a permit have their vehicle 
inspected and watch a videotape on ecology the seashore issues 
about 2000 permits a year cape cod national seashore chief ranger 
tony bonanno said friday 
all dune areas are off limits except a few tracts with deeded 
access rights 
the ruling reinforces the fact that we have taken the 
appropriate steps to meet the natural resource objectives and meet 
the public interest cape cod national seashore chief ranger tony 
bonanno said friday 
the cape cod national seashore created by the 1961 federal 
seashore act enacted a resource management plan in august 1981 to 
control increasing numbers of beachgoers and wheeled vehicles the 
three conservation groups sued the day the plan took effect 
the original plan allowed vehicles on 12 miles of beach from 
april to november and on a 25mile stretch in eastham in winter 
after an order from nelson the plan was amended in 1985 
the court is basically saying yes the 85 plan is a 
resonable plan it addresses adequately the balance of different 
uses accommodates all visitors to the seashore and protects its 
resources bonanno said 
conservationists say offroad vehicle use is prohibited under 
the seashore act which bans action that would be incompatible 
with the preservation of the unique flora and fauna or the 
physiographic conditions now prevailing 
but the act permits recreational development for activities 
such as fishing camping and sailing that is environmentally 
compatible and appropriate to the beach the government can 
ban offroad vehicle use if found to have adverse effects on soil 
vegetation or wildlife habitats 
the law foundation said policing drivers is difficult that even 
small incursions on tender dune grass are harmful and that the 
seashore has handed over onefifth of the beach to drivers who 
comprise just 3 percent of its 6 million annual users 
the law did not envision the rampant offroad vehicle use that 
has gone on since the seashore was created foundation staff 
scientist paul hauge said friday 
bonanno said rangers last year filed 236 reports of dune buggy 
violations issuing about 100 fines of 50 and 100 warnings 
seashore officials said most beach drivers are fishermen needing 
access to the tip of race point 
a national park service survey found that only a small 
percentage of seashore visitors opposed vehicle use or said they 
were displaced by it 
</TEXT>
