<TEXT>
a company accused of reneging on a drought 
insurance offer said friday it would issue an additional 10 
million in total coverage for farmers in 10 midwest states 
but one insurance official said federal insurance cos plan was 
unacceptable 
federal a subsidiary of warrenbased chubb group insurance 
cos has been accused of backing off a promise to issue policies 
that pay off if rainfall falls below a certain level 
chubb says the flood of applications in the final days of the 
enrollment period which lasted from may 1 to june 17 exceeded the 
amount of coverage it wanted to provide and that it cannot fill 
all the applications 
the company initially planned to issue 30 million but increased 
the total coverage to 40 million which will protect about 800 
farmers chubb said friday it made the decision after talking with 
insurance commissioners in the affected states 
the 6000 farmers who do not receive insurance will get twice 
the amount of their premium returned said chubb spokeswoman mary 
lu korkuch premiums already have been returned to insurance 
agents she said 
another 1000 farmers whose applications were received june 16 
or later will get only their premium back she said 
farmers arent losing money she said they just might 
not get the insurance they want 
applications for about 350 million in total coverage are not 
being accepted because they exceed the 40 million limit she said 
chubb said friday any assertion that it was bound to accept all 
applications was without merit and would be subject to a very 
vigorous defense the company said nearly all the applications 
clearly indicate that policies would be issued only after 
acceptance by the insurer 
its hogwash iowa insurance commissioner william hager said 
of that contention 
the application form we approved for use in iowa specifically 
provides that once the premium is submitted coverage is bound 
hager said 
we simply are not going to tolerate by analogy a company 
that issues a policy finds out that the building is burning and 
says whoops we really didnt mean we were going to cover the 
loss the iowa commissioner said 
iowa and ohio officials said their states are prepared to take 
legal action if necessary while minnesota will seek to revoke the 
companys state license to do business if it does not provide the 
coverage 
an estimated 450 ohio farmers applied and sent in premiums for 
the insurance said neil rector deputy director of the ohio 
department of insurance about 10 percent of them would be covered 
under chubbs proposal he said 
minnesota commerce commissioner michael hatch estimates 1000 
farmers from his state applied for a total of 40 million in 
coverage 
other states whose farmers sought the coverage are indiana 
iowa illinois kentucky michigan missouri tennessee and 
wisconsin 
we increased our capacity for this program from 30 million to 
40 million in the hope that this additional coverage will provide 
help to midwestern farmers during this very difficult period 
chubb said in a written statement 
lawsuits have been filed against chubb by indiana farmers 
alleging the company acted in bad faith by reneging on the 
insurance and some farmers in tennessee and kentucky told an agent 
to send the premium refunds back to chubb and demand the coverage 
be provided 
rector said chubb has not been threatened with license 
revocation in ohio but weve told them that the departments 
position is theyre on the hook 
ms korkuch said she could not comment on the lawsuits and said 
they have not been resolved she also said she had no comment on 
what the company would do if farmers refuse to accept the refunds 
