<TEXT>
rebels mounted three attacks in 
northern and central nicaragua in violation of a truce with the 
sandinista government the defense ministry said friday 
its report said three of the ussupported rebels known as 
contras and one civilian were killed in the fighting and the 
contras kidnapped 20 people 
the ministry statement said that in one of the attacks on 
thursday three contras died in a shootout with an army patrol in 
northern matagalpa province 
it also said the contras ambushed an army truck in northern 
jinotega province kidnapping 16 people on board and that four 
other people were abducted by the rebels and a civilian was killed 
in central chontales province 
the statement gave no details of the fighting and said nothing 
of any government casualties the contras and the leftist 
sandinista government have accused each other of truce violations 
on and off since the ceasefire began march 21 
representatives from both sides held meetings to try to reach a 
peace accord without success the last round of talks in june ended 
in deadlock and no new meetings were scheduled 
the sandinistas celebrate nine years in power next tuesday the 
insurrection they led in july 1979 ended 42 years of rule by the 
rightist proamerican somoza dynasty 
the army announced on friday a series of military exercises to 
defend managua the capital in case of attack the sandinistas 
have long claimed the united states eventually plans to invade 
nicaragua 
on monday the sandinistas expelled us ambassador richard 
melton and seven other us diplomats accusing them of conspiring 
to undermine the government 
the interior ministry announced friday night the suspension of 
the radio program el despertar the awakening for 
transmitting false information the statement read over 
staterun radio did not say how long the suspension would be in 
effect 
