<TEXT>
americas trade deficit expanded only slightly in may and 
inflation remained moderate in june the government said today in 
encouraging reports that sent the dollar soaring 
the commerce department said the trade deficit rose to 109 
billion in may from a revised 103 billion in april but the 
number was still the second smallest in almost three years and well 
within economists expectations 
imports rose 34 percent to about 376 billion but the 
increase was offset by a 23 percent increase in exports which 
rose to about 266 billion very close to the record level for 
exports set in march 
the labor department said wholesale prices rose a moderate 04 
percent in june despite a searing drought that sent prices for raw 
food soaring at their steepest pace in more than 2 years 
in other reports released today the federal reserve said june 
industrial production rose 04 percent largely because of higher 
electricity output and the commerce department said may business 
inventories rose 06 percent which suggested a slight slowdown in 
sales 
but those reports werent watched as closely as the news on 
trade and inflation which was better than many thought and sent 
money traders scrambling to buy dollars the currencys strong 
advance prompted some central banks to sell dollars in the market 
to stem the rise traders reported 
