<DOCNO> AP880715-0263 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
everyone is worrying about inflation but a lot 
of folks are doing something about it and they just might have the 
final say 
those folks are consumers and they have been resisting price 
increases for several years now and seem intent on continuing their 
vigilance this isnt an assumption the activity shows up in 
official statistics 
the measurements that prove the case are the gross national 
product implicit price deflator and the gross national product 
fixedweight price index 
for practical purposes the important thing to remember about 
the fixedweight price index is that it measures only changes in 
prices and these prices are of the same products month after month 
the implicit price deflator is a bit more sophisticated 
measuring not just prices but changes in the composition of 
purchases it has been rising much more slowly than its more rigid 
cousin 
the importance of this disparity is that it indicates a 
resistance to price increases by consumers they have continued to 
buy but they have avoided items rising in price and when 
possible switched to more stable items 
such behavior is enormously significant suggesting a 
fundamental change in consumer attitudes from earlier periods 
an analysis by wright investors service contrasts this price 
resistance to the attitude that prevailed during much of the 1960s 
and 1970s when consumers simply went ahead and bought in fact 
many consumers bought more than they needed at any given time 
convinced that future prices would be even higher 
those were very different times consumers were fatalistic 
convinced that they could have little impact on pricing factors 
why try to hold down the budget when opec was forcing up gasoline 
and heating oil prices 
but there was more to it than that many workers had broad 
costofliving increases built into union contracts enabling them 
to offset higher prices industrys attitude toward wage increases 
was simply to give in and then raise prices and for reasons not 
explained logically there existed a feeling that inflation was a 
way of life that couldnt be disciplined 
in those days the two indicators of inflation rose in relation 
to each other it was only in the 1980s that they began to diverge 
indicating that consumers felt they could do something about 
pricing such as declining to buy 
this relatively new sense of consumer power is especially 
noticeable in automobile sales which for several years have relied 
on incentives take away those incentives and sales dive replace 
them and they rise again 
it has occurred in housing sales as well as many wouldbe 
sellers in some of the more affluent neighborhoods have discovered 
over the past few months houses that a year ago sold within days 
of listing now remain on the market for months even though 
mortgages have been relatively easy to obtain 
some retailers are complaining but in view of todays consumer 
attitude you might say they should have known better early this 
year apparel prices rose sharply followed quickly by sales 
problems for many apparel retailers 
the new attitude hasnt been lost on producers of services and 
manufactured goods many of whom have chosen to absorb higher costs 
in order to maintain sales rather than pass on increases and lose 
customer loyalty 
the resistance applies even to interest rates strange as it 
sounds to some folks who couldnt get an appointment with a bank 
loan officer a few years ago many banks now advertise for 
customers especially for home loans 
the new attitude can be found in of all places wage 
settlements learning from the 1970s when wage increases were more 
than offset by price increases workers have been seeking less 
opting instead for wageprice stability 
it is encouraging news this inflation fight by a lot of 
ordinary folks together they make an antiinflation force as 
strong as almost any other perhaps even matching the vaunted power 
of the august federal reserve board 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

