<TEXT>
german automaker audi says it will appeal a 
jurys award of nearly 22 million to a braindamaged woman 
injured in a crash the jury blamed partly on an alleged defect in 
her car 
a superior court jury made the award wednesday to diane rose 
53 who was injured when her 1981 audi 5000s crashed into a wall as 
she drove down benedict canyon in may 1982 
the jury agreed with mrs roses lawyers contention that the 
accident was caused by a design defect that places the cars gas 
and brake pedals too close together jurors found audi 75 percent 
at fault and ms rose 25 percent responsible for leaving her seat 
belt unbuckled 
audi denies there is any defect and argued that mrs rose took 
a curve too fast and lost control said spokesman joseph bennett at 
audi of america inc in troy mich the company a division of 
volkswagen of america inc will appeal the decision he said 
thursday 
mrs rose was alone in the car and there were no witnesses the 
case rested on testimony of expert witnesses from each side 
the case is unrelated to uncontrolled acceleration problems in 
automatictransmission audi 5000s models that prompted a 1987 
recall of all 240000 audi 5000 models sold in this country since 
1978 the cars were fitted with shiftlock devices which require a 
driver to press the brake pedal before operating the automatic 
transmission 
in addition to the almost 22 million award to mrs rose the 
jury awarded her husband joseph 700000 for his suffering 
mrs rose suffered a broken neck brain damage and bladder 
problems and has incurred medical expenses of more than 500000 
her lawyers said 
the jury found volkwagen innocent of malice despite the design 
defect ruling the company did not deliberately disregard the 
rights and safety of others 
the audi 5000 has been recalled twice before in 1982 to raise 
the height of the brake pedal so the brakes will work even if the 
driver steps on the brake and accelerator pedal at the same time 
and in 1981 to anchor floor carpets so they couldnt slide up over 
the accelerator and keep it from rising when the drivers foot is 
removed 
</TEXT>
